Introduction

In this report, well examine at Vera Institute data on incarceration to determine if theres a chance for radical change. It calls for a radical rethinking of the most severe criminal penalty we have: jail. It accomplishes this by showing us how incarceration differs by race.We dont have a complete picture of how the jail population varies based on the data. The information provides the years. Well concentrate on annual prison admissions by county (total prison adm) to do so.In the United States, the tale of mass incarceration is a story about race. As incarceration rates in jails and prisons rose to historically unprecedented levels in the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s, the responsibilities of that development did not fall equally on all communities. The impact has been disastrous for black people in particular, ripping a swath of destruction through communities economic and social fiber, assuring the perpetuation of systematic inequity that undermines our countrys basic ideals.

Summary Information

While looking through the data my interest leaned at comparing white and black jail populations. I started off looking at Highest Black Population in A County, r highest_black_county, and Highest White Population in A County r highest_white_county. Also the counties with the lowest jail population r lowest_black_wa, and r lowest_white_wa.Also Highest jail Population Year by race, r black_highest_year and r white_highest_year. Also Largest race jail population in WA county wise r highest_black_wa and r highest_white_wa. I am from Snohomish County, I wanted to see the number from my area, " r white_jail_pop_in_snohomish_county, andr black_jail_pop_in_snohomish_county".

Time Trend Chart

Included the chart to show the proportions of jailed people with respect to race and population over years.Blacks have long outnumbered whites in U.S. prisons. But a significant decline in the number of black prisoners has steadily narrowed the gap over the past decade, according to new data from the Bureau of Justice Statistics.
